text:
In the circuit shown in Figure 3.15, diodes $D_1$ and $D_2$ differ only in their cross-sectional areas, being identical in all other respects. Calculate the current passing through each diode.

Figure 3.15 depicts a diode circuit.
image_name: Figure 3.15 Diode circuit
description:
[
name: V1, type: VoltageSource, value: V1, ports: {Np: Vi, Nn: GND}
name: R1, type: Resistor, value: R1, ports: {N1: Vi, N2: X1}
name: D1, type: Diode, ports: {Na: X1, Nc: GND}
name: D2, type: Diode, ports: {Na: X1, Nc: GND}
]
extrainfo: The circuit is composed of a voltage source V1 connected in series with a resistor R1, which is then connected in parallel with diodes D1 and D2. Node X1 links R1 to the anodes of both diodes, with the cathodes of the diodes connected to ground.

To solve this, we need to employ the exponential equation due to the absence of the device area in both the ideal and constant-voltage models. We have

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{in} = I_{D1} + I_{D2} \tag{3.12}
\end{equation*}
$$

We also set the voltages across $D_1$ and $D_2$ equal:

$$
\begin{equation*}
V_T \ln \frac{I_{D1}}{I_{S1}} = V_T \ln \frac{I_{D2}}{I_{S2}} \tag{3.13}
\end{equation*}
$$

This simplifies to:

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{I_{D1}}{I_{S1}} = \frac{I_{D2}}{I_{S2}} \tag{3.14}
\end{equation*}
$$

Solving equations (3.13) and (3.15) simultaneously yields:

$$
\begin{align*}
& I_{D1} = \frac{I_{in}}{1+\frac{I_{S2}}{I_{S1}}}  \tag{3.15}\\
& I_{D2} = \frac{I_{in}}{1+\frac{I_{S1}}{I_{S2}}} \tag{3.16}
\end{align*}
$$

As anticipated, if $I_{S1} = I_{S2}$, then $I_{D1} = I_{D2} = \frac{I_{in}}{2}$.

Exercise: For the circuit in Figure 3.15, express $V_D$ in terms of $I_{in}, I_{S1}$, and $I_{S2}$.
