Our handling of diodes has allowed for significant voltage and current fluctuations, necessitating a comprehensive model like the exponential I/V characteristic. This is referred to as "large-signal operation," and the exponential characteristic is known as the "large-signal model," highlighting its ability to handle any signal magnitude. However, this model can complicate analysis and hinder intuitive understanding of circuit behavior, especially as the number of nonlinear devices increases, making manual analysis unfeasible.

The ideal and constant-voltage diode models partially address these issues, but the sharp nonlinearity at the turn-on point remains problematic. An example illustrates this general challenge:

A student, having lost their 2.4-V cellphone charger, fails to find adaptors below 3 V in local stores. They decide to build a circuit, shown in Fig. 3.19, with three identical diodes in forward bias to achieve a total voltage of $V_{\text {out }}=3 V_{D} \approx 2.4 \mathrm{~V}$, while resistor $R_{1}$ compensates for the remaining 600 mV. The cellphone's current draw is ignored. (a) Calculate the reverse saturation current, $I_{S 1}$, for $V_{\text {out }}=2.4 \mathrm{~V}$. (b) Determine $V_{\text {out }}$ if the adaptor voltage is actually 3.1 V.

The circuit includes a voltage source (Vad = 3V), a current source (Ix), a resistor (R1 = 100Ω), and three diodes (D1, D2, D3) in series. The diodes are forward-biased, and the total output voltage (Vout) is approximately 2.4V. The resistor R1 sustains the remaining 600mV. The circuit is used to power a cellphone, with the current through the diodes equal to the current through the resistor.

Solution
(a) With $V_{\text {out }}=2.4 \mathrm{~V}$, the current through $R_{1}$ is

$$
\begin{align*}
I_{X} & =\frac{V_{\text {ad }}-V_{\text {out }}}{R_{1}}  \tag{3.33}\\
& =6 \mathrm{~mA} . \tag{3.34}
\end{align*}
$$

Each diode carries $I_{X}$, so

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{X}=I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{D}}{V_{T}} \tag{3.35}
\end{equation*}
$$

Thus,

$$
\begin{equation*}
6 \mathrm{~mA}=I_{S} \exp \frac{800 \mathrm{mV}}{26 \mathrm{mV}} \tag{3.36}
\end{equation*}
$$

and

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{S}=2.602 \times 10^{-16} \mathrm{~A} \tag{3.37}
\end{equation*}
$$

(b) If $V_{\text {ad }}$ increases to 3.1 V, $V_{\text {out }}$ should rise slightly. Assuming $V_{\text {out }}$ remains at 2.4 V, the extra 0.1 V drops across $R_{1}$, increasing $I_{X}$ to 7 mA. Given the logarithmic current-voltage relationship, the change from 6 mA to 7 mA results in a minor $V_{\text {out }}$ adjustment.

Quantitative analysis starts with $I_{X}=7 \mathrm{~mA}$ and proceeds iteratively:

$$
\begin{align*}
V_{\text {out }} & =3 V_{D}  \tag{3.38}\\
& =3 V_{T} \ln \frac{I_{X}}{I_{S}}  \tag{3.39}\\
& =2.412 \mathrm{~V} \tag{3.40}
\end{align*}
$$

This $V_{\text {out }}$ yields a new $I_{X}$:

$$
\begin{align*}
I_{X} & =\frac{V_{\text {ad }}-V_{\text {out }}}{R_{1}}  \tag{3.41}\\
& =6.88 \mathrm{~mA} \tag{3.42}
\end{align*}
$$

which translates to a new $V_{\text {out }}$:

$$
\begin{align*}
V_{\text {out }} & =3 V_{D}  \tag{3.43}\\
& =2.411 \mathrm{~V} . \tag{3.44}
\end{align*}
$$

The minimal difference between (3.40) and (3.44) indicates $V_{\text {out }}=2.411 \mathrm{~V}$ with high accuracy. The constant-voltage diode model is inadequate here.

