This scenario exemplifies small "perturbations" in circuits. The 0.1 V increase in $V_{a d}$ leads to minor voltage and current changes, prompting the search for a simpler analysis method to replace nonlinear equations and iterative procedures. While the example isn't overly complex, subsequent chapters will show that circuits with devices like transistors can become intractable with nonlinear equations.

This leads to the crucial concept of "small-signal operation," where circuits undergo minor voltage and current changes, allowing simplification via "small-signal models" for nonlinear devices. These models are linear, enabling standard circuit analysis without iteration. The definition of "small" will be clarified later.

To grasp small-signal operation, consider diode $D_{1}$ in Fig. 3.20(a), sustaining voltage $V_{D 1}$ and current $I_{D 1}$ [point $A$ in Fig. 3.20(b)]. A circuit perturbation causes a small voltage change $\Delta V_{D}$ [point $B$ in Fig. 3.20(c)]. How do we predict the current change, $\Delta I_{D}$? Starting with the nonlinear characteristic:

$$
\begin{align*}
I_{D 2} & =I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{D 1}+\Delta V}{V_{T}}  \tag{3.45}\\
& =I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{D 1}}{V_{T}} \exp \frac{\Delta V}{V_{T}} \tag{3.46}
\end{align*}
$$

If $\Delta V \ll V_{T}$, then $\exp \left(\Delta V / V_{T}\right) \approx 1+\Delta V / V_{T}$, and

$$
\begin{align*}
I_{D 2} & =I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{D 1}}{V_{T}}+\frac{\Delta V}{V_{T}} I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{D 1}}{V_{T}}  \tag{3.47}\\
& =I_{D 1}+\frac{\Delta V}{V_{T}} I_{D 1} \tag{3.48}
\end{align*}
$$

Thus,

$$
\begin{equation*}
\Delta I_{D}=\frac{\Delta V}{V_{T}} I_{D 1} \tag{3.49}
\end{equation*}
$$

The key observation is that $\Delta I_{D}$ is a linear function of $\Delta V$, with a proportionality factor of $I_{D 1} / V_{T}$. This result is intuitive: for small $V_{D}$ changes, the curve section in Fig. 3.20(c) between points $A$ and $B$ can be approximated by a straight line, with a slope equal to the local curve slope.

This approximation is shown in Fig. 3.21, where the linear section between points A and B represents the small-signal conductance. The change in current (ΔI_D) and voltage (ΔV_D) between these points illustrates the linear approximation.

In essence,

$$
\begin{align*}
\frac{\Delta I_{D}}{\Delta V_{D}} & =\left.\frac{d I_{D}}{d V_{D}}\right|_{V D=V D 1}  \tag{3.50}\\
& =\frac{I_{S}}{V_{T}} \exp \frac{V_{D 1}}{V_{T}}  \tag{3.51}\\
& =\frac{I_{D 1}}{V_{T}} \tag{3.52}
\end{align*}
$$

yielding the same result as Eq. (3.49).

To summarize, for small voltage changes across a diode (much less than $V_{T}$), the current change is given by Eq. (3.49). For small-signal analysis, we assume operation at a point like $A$ in Fig. 3.21 and, due to a small perturbation, move to point $B$ along a straight line with a slope equal to the local curve slope (i.e., $d I_{D} / d V_{D}$ at $V_{D}=V_{D 1}$ or $I_{D}=I_{D 1}$). Point $A$ is the "bias" or "operating" point.

Example: A diode is biased at 1 mA. (a) Calculate the current change for a 1 mV $V_{D}$ change. (b) Determine the voltage change for a 10% $I_{D}$ change.

Solution: (a) Using Eq. (3.53),

$$
\begin{align*}
\Delta I_{D} & =\frac{I_{D}}{V_{T}} \Delta V_{D}  \tag{3.53}\\
& =38.4 \mu \mathrm{~A} . \tag{3.54}
\end{align*}
$$

(b) From Eq. (3.55),

$$
\begin{align*}
\Delta V_{D} & =\frac{V_{T}}{I_{D}} \Delta I_{D}  \tag{3.55}\\
& =\left(\frac{26 \mathrm{mV}}{1 \mathrm{~mA}}\right) \times(0.1 \mathrm{~mA})  \tag{3.56}\\
& =2.6 \mathrm{mV} \tag{3.57}
\end{align*}
$$

