Eq. (3.58) reveals an interesting aspect of small-signal operation: for small current and voltage changes, the diode behaves as a linear resistor. Analogous to Ohm's Law, we define the "small-signal resistance" as:

$$
\begin{equation*}
r_{d}=\frac{V_{T}}{I_{D}} \tag{3.58}
\end{equation*}
$$

This is also the "incremental" resistance, emphasizing its validity for small changes. In the example, $r_{d}=26 \Omega$.

Fig. 3.22(a) summarizes the results for a forward-biased diode. For bias calculations, the diode is replaced with an ideal voltage source $V_{D, o n}$, and for small changes, with a resistor $r_{d}$. For example, the circuit in Fig. 3.22(b) is transformed to Fig. 3.22(c) for small $V_{1}$ and $V_{\text {out }}$ changes. Note that $v_{1}$ and $v_{\text {out }}$ represent voltage changes and are called small-signal quantities. Small-signal voltages and currents are denoted by lowercase letters.

