Our exploration of diodes to date has permitted substantial voltage and current fluctuations, necessitating a comprehensive model like the exponential I/V characteristic. This mode of operation is termed "large-signal operation," and the exponential characteristic is known as the "large-signal model," highlighting its capacity to handle diverse signal magnitudes. Nevertheless, as prior examples have shown, this model can complicate analysis and hinder intuitive comprehension of circuit behavior. Additionally, as the number of nonlinear devices in a circuit grows, manual analysis becomes increasingly unfeasible.

Although the ideal and constant-voltage diode models partially address these challenges, the abrupt nonlinearity at the turn-on point remains an issue. The following example demonstrates this general difficulty.

3.17

An electronics student, having misplaced his 2.4-V cellphone charger, searches various stores without finding adaptors with outputs below 3 V. He decides to apply his electronics knowledge and constructs the circuit depicted in Fig. 3.19, where three identical forward-biased diodes generate a combined voltage of $V_{\text {out }}=3 V_{D} \approx 2.4 \mathrm{~V}$, and resistor $R_{1}$ supports the remaining 600 mV. Ignore the current drawn by the cellphone. ${ }^{6}$ (a) Calculate the reverse saturation current, $I_{S 1}$, for $V_{\text {out }}=2.4 \mathrm{~V}$. (b) Determine $V_{\text {out }}$ if the adaptor voltage is actually 3.1 V.

