extrainfo:This circuit comprises a voltage source (Vad = 3V), a current source (Ix), a resistor (R1 = 100Ω), and three diodes (D1, D2, D3) in series. The diodes are forward-biased, and the total output voltage (Vout) is approximately 2.4V. The resistor R1 sustains the remaining 600mV. The circuit is used to power a cellphone, with the current through the diodes being equal to the current through the resistor.

Solution
(a) For $V_{\text {out }}=2.4 \mathrm{~V}$, the current through $R_{1}$ is

$$
\begin{align*}
I_{X} & =\frac{V_{\text {ad }}-V_{\text {out }}}{R_{1}}  \tag{3.33}\\
& =6 \mathrm{~mA} . \tag{3.34}
\end{align*}
$$

We observe that each diode carries $I_{X}$, hence

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{X}=I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{D}}{V_{T}} \tag{3.35}
\end{equation*}
$$

Thus,

$$
\begin{equation*}
6 \mathrm{~mA}=I_{S} \exp \frac{800 \mathrm{mV}}{26 \mathrm{mV}} \tag{3.36}
\end{equation*}
$$

and

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{S}=2.602 \times 10^{-16} \mathrm{~A} \tag{3.37}
\end{equation*}
$$

(b) If $V_{\text {ad }}$ rises to 3.1 V, we anticipate a slight increase in $V_{\text {out }}$. To comprehend this, assume $V_{\text {out }}$ remains constant at 2.4 V. Consequently, the extra 0.1 V must drop across $R_{1}$, boosting $I_{X}$ to 7 mA. Given the voltage across each diode has a logarithmic dependence on the current, the shift from 6 mA to 7 mA indeed results in a minor change in $V_{\text {out }}{ }^{7}$

To quantitatively analyze the circuit, we start with $I_{X}=7 \mathrm{~mA}$ and iterate:

$$
\begin{align*}
V_{\text {out }} & =3 V_{D}  \tag{3.38}\\
& =3 V_{T} \ln \frac{I_{X}}{I_{S}}  \tag{3.39}\\
& =2.412 \mathrm{~V} \tag{3.40}
\end{align*}
$$

This $V_{\text {out }}$ value yields a new $I_{X}$:

$$
\begin{align*}
I_{X} & =\frac{V_{\text {ad }}-V_{\text {out }}}{R_{1}}  \tag{3.41}\\
& =6.88 \mathrm{~mA} \tag{3.42}
\end{align*}
$$

which corresponds to a new $V_{\text {out }}$:

$$
\begin{align*}
V_{\text {out }} & =3 V_{D}  \tag{3.43}\\
& =2.411 \mathrm{~V} . \tag{3.44}
\end{align*}
$$

Noting the minimal discrepancy between (3.40) and (3.44), we conclude that $V_{\text {out }}=2.411 \mathrm{~V}$ with high precision. The constant-voltage diode model would be ineffective in this scenario.

