The scenario described above exemplifies small "perturbations" in circuits. The 0.1 V increase in $V_{a d}$ from 3 V to 3.1 V induces minor alterations in the circuit's voltages and currents, prompting us to seek a simpler analysis technique that can supplant the nonlinear equations and the requisite iterative process. While the example may not present an excessively complex problem, subsequent chapters will demonstrate that circuits with intricate devices like transistors can become become inanalyzable if the
To retain the nonlinear equations. These realization leads us to the crucial concept of "small-signal operation," where the circuit undergoes only minor fluctuations in voltages and currents, allowing simplification through the employment of "small-signal models" for nonlinear devices. The appeal of in the linearity of these models, which permits standard circuit analysis and eliminates the need for iteration. The meaning for what constitutes a "small" change will be clarified later.

To deepen our understanding of small-signal operation, consider diode $D_{1}$ in Fig. 3.20(a), which maintains a voltage $V_{D 1}$ and conducts a current $I_{D 1}$ [point $A$ in Fig. 3.20(b)]. Now, suppose a perturbation in the circuit induces the diode voltage by a slight amount $\Delta V_{D}$ [point $B$ in Fig. 3.20(c)]. How can we predict the corresponding change in the diode current, $\Delta I_{D}$? We start with the nonlinear characteristic:

$$
\begin{align*}
I_{D 2} & =I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{D 1}+\Delta V}{V_{T}}  \tag{3.45}\\
& =I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{D 1}}{V_{T}} \exp \frac{\Delta V}{V_{T}} \tag{3.46}
\end{align*}
$$

If $\Delta V \ll V_{T}$, then $\exp \left(\Delta V / V_{T}\right) \approx 1+\Delta V / V_{T}$, and

$$
\begin{align*}
I_{D 2} & =I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{D 1}}{V_{T}}+\frac{\Delta V}{V_{T}} I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{D 1}}{V_{T}}  \tag{3.47}\\
& =I_{D 1}+\frac{\Delta V}{V_{T}} I_{D 1} \tag{3.48}
\end{align*}
$$

Thus,

$$
\begin{equation*}
\Delta I_{D}=\frac{\Delta V}{V_{T}} I_{D 1} \tag{3.49}
\end{equation*}
$$

The key observation is that $\Delta I_{D}$ is a linear function of $\Delta V$, with a proportionality constant equal to $I_{D 1} / V_{T}$. (Larger values of $I_{D 1}$ result in a greater $\Delta I_{D}$ for a given $\Delta V_{D}$. The importance of this trend will be evident later.)

This result should not be unexpected: if the change in $V_{D}$ is small, the segment of the characteristic in Fig. 3.20(c) between points $A$ and $B$ can be approximated by a straight line (Fig. 3.21), with a slope equal to the local slope of the characteristic.

