A sinusoidal signal characterized by a peak amplitude of \( V_{p} \) and a direct current (DC) offset of \( V_{0} \) can be represented as \( V(t) = V_{0} + V_{p} \cos(\omega t) \). When such a signal is applied across a diode and \( V_{p} \) is significantly smaller than the thermal voltage \( V_{T} \), we need to determine the resulting diode current.

To solve this, we first visualize the signal waveform as depicted in Figure 3.23(a). By rotating this diagram by \( 90^{\circ} \), as shown in Figure 3.23(b), we align the vertical axis with the voltage axis of the diode characteristic. Given that the signal swing is much less than \( V_{T} \), we can consider \( V_{0} \) and the corresponding current \( I_{0} \) as the bias point of the diode, and \( V_{p} \) as a small perturbation. This leads to the following equations:

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{0} = I_{S} \exp\left{V_{0}}{V_{T}} \tag{3.59}
\end{equation*}
$$

and

$$
\begin{equation*}
r_{d} = \frac{V_{T}}{I_{0}} \tag{3.60}
\end{equation*}
$$

Thus, the peak current can be expressed as

$$
\begin{align*}
I_{p} & = \frac{V_{p}}{r_{d}} \tag{3.61}\\
& = \frac{I_{0}}{V_{T}} V_{p} \tag{3.62}
\end{align*}
$$

The graphs provided in Figures 3.23(a) and 3.23(b) show the sinusoidal input with a DC offset and the diode's response to this input, respectively. The diode current as a function of time can be expressed as

$$
\begin{align*}
I_{D}(t) & = I_{0} + I_{p} \cos(\omega t) \tag{3.63}\\
& = I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{0}}{V_{T}} + \frac{I_{0}}{V_{T}} V_{p} \cos(\omega t) \tag{3.64}
\end{align*}
$$

An exercise is presented to calculate the saturation current \( I_{S} \) given a peak current of 0.1 mA in response to \( V_{0} = 800 \) mV and \( V_{p} = 1.5 \) mV.

This example highlights the utility of small-signal analysis. If \( V_{p} \) were large, we would need to solve a more complex equation, which is much more difficult than the linear calculations performed here.

In the derivation leading to Equation (3.49), we assumed a small change in \( V_{D} \) and obtained the resulting change in \( I_{D} \). Starting with \( V_{D} = V_{T} \ln(I_{D} / I_{S}) \), we now investigate the reverse case, i.e., \( I_{D} \) changes by a small amount and we wish to compute the change in \( V_{D} \).

Denoting the change in \( V_{D} \) by \( \Delta V_{D} \), we have

$$
\begin{align*}
V_{D 1} + \Delta V_{D} & = V_{T} \ln \frac{I_{D 1} + \Delta I_{D}}{I_{S}} \tag{3.66}\\
& = V_{T} \ln \left[\frac{I_{D 1}}{I_{S}}\left(1 + \frac{\Delta I_{D}}{I_{D 1}}\right)\right] \tag{3.67}\\
& = V_{T} \ln \frac{I_{D 1}}{I_{S}} + V_{T} \ln \left(1 + \frac{\Delta I_{D}}{I_{D 1}}\right) \tag{3.68}
\end{align*}
$$

For small-signal operation, we assume \( \Delta I_{D} \ll I_{D 1} \) and note that \( \ln(1 + \epsilon) \approx \epsilon \) if \( \epsilon \ll 1 \). Thus,

$$
\begin{equation*}
\Delta V_{D} = V_{T} \cdot \frac{\Delta I_{D}}{I_{D 1}} \tag{3.69}
\end{equation*}
$$

which is the same as Equation (3.49). Figure 3.24 illustrates the two cases, distinguishing between the cause and the effect.

An exercise is given to repeat the above example by taking the derivative of the diode voltage equation with respect to \( I_{D} \).

With our understanding of small-signal operation, we now revisit Example 3.17.

Example 3.21 is repeated with the aid of a small-signal model for the diodes. Since each diode carries \( I_{D 1} = 6 \) mA with an adaptor voltage of 3 V and \( V_{D 1} = 800 \) mV, we can construct the small-signal model shown in Figure 3.25, where \( v_{ad} = 100 \) mV and \( r_{d} = (26 \) mV) / (6 \) mA) = 4.33 \( \Omega \). We can then write:

$$
\begin{align*}
v_{\text{out}} & = \frac{3 r_{d}}{R_{1} + 3 r_{d}} v_{ad} \tag{3.70}\\
& = 11.5 \text{mV} \tag{3.71}
\end{align*}
$$

This indicates that a 100-mV change in \( V_{ad} \) yields an 11.5-mV change in \( V_{\text{out}} \). In Example 3.17, the solution of nonlinear diode equations predicted an 11-mV change in \( V_{\text{out}} \). The small-signal analysis, therefore, offers reasonable accuracy while requiring much less computational effort.

An exercise is given to repeat Examples 3.17 and 3.21 if the value of \( R_{1} \) in Figure 3.19 is changed to 200 \( \Omega \).

Considering the power of today's computer software tools, one might question the necessity of the small-signal model. Indeed, sophisticated simulation tools are utilized in the design of integrated circuits today, but the intuition gained by hand analysis of a circuit is invaluable in understanding fundamental limitations and various trade-offs that eventually lead to a compromise in the design. A good circuit designer analyzes and understands the circuit before giving it to the computer for a more accurate analysis, while a bad circuit designer allows the computer to think for him/her.

In Examples 3.17 and 3.21, the current drawn by the cellphone is neglected. Now, as shown in Figure 3.26, suppose the load pulls a current of 0.5 mA and determine \( V_{\text{out}} \).

Since the current flowing through the diodes decreases by 0.5 mA and this change is much less than the bias current (6 mA), we write the change in the output voltage as:

$$
\begin{align*}
\Delta V_{\text{out}} & = \Delta I_{D} \cdot (3 r_{d}) \tag{3.72}\\
& = 0.5 \text{mA} (3 \times 4.33 \Omega) \tag{3.73}\\
& = 6.5 \text{mV} \tag{3.74}
\end{align*}
$$

An exercise is given to repeat the above example if \( R_{1} \) is reduced to 80 \( \Omega \).

The analysis of circuits containing diodes (and other nonlinear devices such as transistors) proceeds in three steps: (1) determine the initial values of voltages and currents (before an input change is applied); (2) develop the small-signal model for each diode (i.e., calculate \( r_{d} \)); (3) replace each diode with its small-signal model and compute the effect of the input change.

A sinusoidal signal with a peak amplitude of $V_{p}$ and a DC offset of $V_{0}$ can be represented as $V(t)=V_{0}+V_{p} \cos \omega t$. When this signal is applied across a diode and $V_{p} \ll V_{T}$, the resulting diode current must be determined.

The signal waveform is depicted in Fig. 3.23(a). As illustrated in Fig. 3.23(b), we rotate this diagram by $90^{\circ}$ so that its vertical axis aligns with the voltage axis of the diode characteristic. With a signal swing much smaller than $V_{T}$, we can consider $V_{0}$ and the corresponding current, $I_{0}$, as the bias point of the diode and $V_{p}$ as a small perturbation. Consequently,

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{0}=I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{0}}{V_{T}} \tag{3.59}
\end{equation*}
$$

and

$$
\begin{equation*}
r_{d}=\frac{V_{T}}{I_{0}} \tag{3.60}
\end{equation*}
$$

Thus, the peak current is simply equal to

$$
\begin{align*}
I_{p} & =V_{p} / r_{d}  \tag{3.61}\\
& =\frac{I_{0}}{V_{T}} V_{p} \tag{3.62}
\end{align*}
$$

Figure 3.23 (a) shows a sinusoidal input along with a DC level, while Figure 3.23 (b) depicts the response of a diode to the sinusoid, resulting in

$$
\begin{align*}
I_{D}(t) & =I_{0}+I_{p} \cos \omega t  \tag{3.63}\\
& =I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{0}}{V_{T}}+\frac{I_{0}}{V_{T}} V_{p} \cos \omega t \tag{3.64}
\end{align*}
$$

Exercise: The diode in the above example produces a peak current of 0.1 mA in response to $V_{0}=800 \mathrm{mV}$ and $V_{p}=1.5 \mathrm{mV}$. Calculate $I_{S}$.

The example demonstrates the utility of small-signal analysis. If $V_{p}$ were large, we would need to solve the following equation:

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{D}(t)=I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{0}+V_{p} \cos \omega t}{V_{T}} \tag{3.65}
\end{equation*}
$$

a task much more difficult than the linear calculations shown above.

In the derivation leading to Eq. (3.49), we assumed a small change in $V_{D}$ and obtained the resulting change in $I_{D}$. Starting with $V_{D}=V_{T} \ln \left(I_{D} / I_{S}\right)$, we now investigate the reverse case, i.e., $I_{D}$ changes by a small amount and we wish to compute the change in $V_{D}$.

Solution: Denoting the change in $V_{D}$ by $\Delta V_{D}$, we have

$$
\begin{align*}
V_{D 1}+\Delta V_{D} & =V_{T} \ln \frac{I_{D 1}+\Delta I_{D}}{I_{S}}  \tag{3.66}\\
& =V_{T} \ln \left[\frac{I_{D 1}}{I_{S}}\left(1+\frac{\Delta I_{D}}{I_{D 1}}\right)\right]  \tag{3.67}\\
& =V_{T} \ln \frac{I_{D 1}}{I_{S}}+V_{T} \ln \left(1+\frac{\Delta I_{D}}{I_{D 1}}\right) \tag{3.68}
\end{align*}
$$

For small-signal operation, we assume $\Delta I_{D} \ll I_{D 1}$ and note that $\ln (1+\epsilon) \approx \epsilon$ if $\epsilon \ll 1$. Thus,

$$
\begin{equation*}
\Delta V_{D}=V_{T} \cdot \frac{\Delta I_{D}}{I_{D 1}} \tag{3.69}
\end{equation*}
$$

which is the same as Eq. (3.49). Figure 3.24 illustrates the two cases, distinguishing between the cause and the effect.

Exercise: Repeat the above example by taking the derivative of the diode voltage equation with respect to $I_{D}$.

With our understanding of small-signal operation, we now revisit Example 3.17.

Example: Repeat part (b) of Example 3.17 with the aid of a small-signal model for the diodes.

Solution: Since each diode carries $I_{D 1}=6 \mathrm{~mA}$ with an adaptor voltage of 3 V and $V_{D 1}=800 \mathrm{mV}$, we can construct the small-signal model shown in Fig. 3.25, where $v_{a d}=100 \mathrm{mV}$ and $r_{d}=(26 \mathrm{mV}) /(6 \mathrm{~mA})=4.33 \Omega$. (As mentioned earlier, the voltages shown in this model denote small changes.) We can thus write:

$$
\begin{align*}
v_{\text {out }} & =\frac{3 r_{d}}{R_{1}+3 r_{d}} v_{a d}  \tag{3.70}\\
& =11.5 \mathrm{mV} . \tag{3.71}
\end{align*}
$$

That is, a 100-mV change in $V_{\text {ad }}$ yields an $11.5-\mathrm{mV}$ change in $V_{\text {out }}$. In Example 3.17, the solution of nonlinear diode equations predicted an $11-\mathrm{mV}$ change in $V_{\text {out }}$. The small-signal analysis therefore offers reasonable accuracy while requiring much less computational effort.

Exercise: Repeat Examples (3.17) and (3.21) if the value of $R_{1}$ in Fig. 3.19 is changed to $200 \Omega$.

Considering the power of today's computer software tools, the reader may wonder if the small-signal model is really necessary. Indeed, we utilize sophisticated simulation tools in the design of integrated circuits today, but the intuition gained by hand analysis of a circuit proves invaluable in understanding fundamental limitations and various trade-offs that eventually lead to a compromise in the design. A good circuit designer analyzes and understands the circuit before giving it to the computer for a more accurate analysis. A bad circuit designer, on the other hand, allows the computer to think for him/her.

In Examples 3.17 and 3.21, the current drawn by the cellphone is neglected. Now suppose, as shown in Fig. 3.26, the load pulls a current of $0.5 \mathrm{~mA}$ and determine $V_{\text {out }}$.

Solution: Since the current flowing through the diodes decreases by 0.5 mA and since this change is much less than the bias current $(6 \mathrm{~mA})$, we write the change in the output voltage as:

$$
\begin{align*}
\Delta V_{\text {out }} & =\Delta I_{D} \cdot\left(3 r_{d}\right)  \tag{3.72}\\
& =0.5 \mathrm{~mA}(3 \times 4.33 \Omega)  \tag{3.73}\\
& =6.5 \mathrm{mV} \tag{3.74}
\end{align*}
$$

Exercise: Repeat the above example if $R_{1}$ is reduced to $80 \Omega$.

Did you know?

What would our life be like without diodes? Forget about cell phones, laptops, and digital cameras. We would not even have radios, TVs, GPS, radars, satellites, power plants, or long-distance telephone communication. And, of course, no Google or Facebook. In essence, we would return to the simple lifestyle of the early 1900s-which might not be that bad after all ...

In summary, the analysis of circuits containing diodes (and other nonlinear devices such as transistors) proceeds in three steps: (1) determine-perhaps with the aid of the constant-voltage model-the initial values of voltages and currents (before an input change is applied); (2) develop the small-signal model for each diode (i.e., calculate $r_{d}$ ); (3) replace each diode with its small-signal model and compute the effect of the input change.

The examined adaptor circuit typically proves insufficient. Due to substantial fluctuations in line voltage, the peak amplitude generated by the transformer and, consequently, the dc output vary significantly, potentially surpassing the maximum tolerable level for the load (e.g., a cellphone). Additionally, the ripple may become notably problematic in many applications. For instance, if the adaptor powers a stereo, the $120-\mathrm{Hz}$ ripple can be audible through the speakers. Moreover, the transformer's finite output impedance results in changes in $V_{\text {out }}$ when the load current varies. For these reasons, the circuit shown in Fig. 3.40(a) is often supplemented with a "voltage regulator" to ensure a consistent output.

We have previously encountered a voltage regulator without explicitly labeling it as such: the circuit analyzed in Example 3.17 delivers a voltage of 2.4 V, experiencing only an $11-\mathrm{mV}$ change in output for a $100-\mathrm{mV}$ variation in input. This leads us to the circuit depicted in Fig. 3.43, which serves as a more adaptable adaptor with a nominal output of $3 V_{D, \text { on }} \approx 2.4 \mathrm{~V}$. However, as discussed in Example 3.22, the output voltage varies with the load current.
