Did you know?

While individual diodes in power supplies may not seem to have a large carbon footprint, the cumulative power consumption of all diodes globally presents a startling picture.

Consider, for example, Google's server farms. It is estimated that Google operates around half a million servers. If each server draws 200 W from a 12-V supply, then each rectifier diode carries an average current of $200 \mathrm{~W} / 12 \mathrm{~V} / 2 \approx 8.5 \mathrm{~A}$. (Assuming two diodes alternately conduct, each carrying half of the server's average current.) With a forward bias of approximately 0.7 V, two diodes consume 12 W, implying that the rectifier diodes in Google's servers dissipate a total power of roughly 6 MW. This is equivalent to the power generated by about 10 nuclear power plants! Indeed, significant efforts are currently focused on "green electronics" to reduce the power consumption of every circuit, including the power supply itself. (Note that our example is quite pessimistic, as computers often use "switching" power supplies for improved efficiency.)

Figure 3.44(a) illustrates another regulator circuit employing a Zener diode. Operating in the reverse breakdown region, $D_{1}$ exhibits a small-signal resistance, $r_{D}$, typically between 1 and $10 \Omega$, thereby providing a relatively constant output despite input variations if $r_{D} \ll R_{1}$. This is evident from the small-signal model in Fig. 3.44(b):

$$
\begin{equation*}
v_{\text {out }}=\frac{r_{D}}{r_{D}+R_{1}} v_{\text {in }} \tag{3.100}
\end{equation*}
$$

For instance, if $r_{D}=5 \Omega$ and $R_{1}=1 \mathrm{k} \Omega$, changes in $V_{\text {in }}$ are attenuated by approximately a factor of 200 in $V_{\text {out }}$. However, the Zener regulator shares the same limitation as the circuit in Fig. 3.43, namely, poor stability under significant variations in load current.

Our brief examination of regulators highlights two critical design aspects: the stability of the output relative to input variations, and the stability of the output relative to load current variations. The former is quantified by "line regulation," defined as $\Delta V_{\text {out }} / \Delta V_{\text {in }}$, and the latter by "load regulation," defined as $\Delta V_{\text {out }} / \Delta I_{L}$.
