Figure 3.44(a) illustrates another regulator circuit employing a Zener diode. Operating in the reverse breakdown region, \( D_{1} \) exhibits a small-signal resistance, \( r_{D} \), typically between 1 and \( 10 \Omega \), thereby providing a relatively stable output despite input variations if \( r_{D} \ll R_{1} \). This is evident from the small-signal model in Fig. 3.44(b):

$$
\begin{equation*}
v_{\text{out}} = \frac{r_{D}}{r_{D} + R_{1}} v_{\text{in}} \tag{3.100}
\end{equation*}
$$

For instance, if \( r_{D} = 5 \Omega \) and \( R_{1} = 1 \text{k} \Omega \), changes in \( V_{\text{in}} \) are attenuated by about a factor of 200 in \( V_{\text{out}} \). However, the Zener regulator shares a drawback with the circuit in Fig. 3.43, namely, poor stability under significant variations in load current.

Our brief examination of regulators reveals two critical design aspects: the stability of the output relative to input variations, and the stability of the output relative to load current variations. The former is quantified by "line regulation," defined as \( \Delta V_{\text{out}} / \Delta V_{\text{in}} \), and the latter by "load regulation," defined as \( \Delta V_{\text{out}} / \Delta I_{L} \).
