Electronic systems commonly use a uniform supply voltage, for instance, 3 V, necessitating that both discrete and integrated circuits function within this voltage level. Nevertheless, certain circuit designs can be significantly streamlined if they operate from a higher voltage, such as 6 V. In such cases, "voltage doublers" are utilized to achieve this. ${ }^{17}$

Prior to delving into voltage doublers, it is beneficial to revisit the fundamental properties of capacitors. Initially, to charge one plate of a capacitor to $+Q$, the opposing plate must be charged to $-Q$. As a result, in the circuit depicted in Fig. 3.54(a), the voltage across $C_{1}$ remains constant even if $V_{i n}$ fluctuates because the right plate of $C_{1}$ cannot acquire or discharge charge $(Q=C V)$. Since $V_{C 1}$ remains stable, any input fluctuation $\Delta V_{\text {in }}$ is directly reflected at the output. This is a crucial observation.

Figure 3.54 (a) illustrates the constancy of voltage across one plate of a capacitor, (b) depicts voltage division.

Furthermore, a capacitive voltage divider, as shown in Fig. 3.54(b), functions as follows. When $V_{i n}$ becomes more positive, the left plate of $C_{1}$ acquires positive charge from $V_{i n}$, necessitating that the right plate absorb an equivalent negative charge from the top plate of $C_{2}$. With the loss of negative charge, the top plate of $C_{2}$ effectively holds more positive charge, causing the bottom plate to draw negative charge from ground. It is important to note that all four plates either gain or lose the same amount of charge due to $C_{1}$ and $C_{2}$ being in series. To calculate the change in output voltage, $\Delta V_{\text {out }}$, resulting from $\Delta V_{\text {in }}$, we express the charge change on $C_{2}$ as $\Delta Q_{2}=C_{2} \cdot \Delta V_{\text {out }}$, which also applies to $C_{1}: \Delta Q_{2}=\Delta Q_{1}$. Consequently, the voltage fluctuation across $C_{1}$ equals $C_{2} \cdot \Delta V_{\text {out }} / C_{1}$. By summing these two voltage changes and equating the result to $\Delta V_{i n}$, we obtain

$$
\begin{equation*}
\Delta V_{\text {in }}=\frac{C_{2}}{C_{1}} \Delta V_{\text {out }}+\Delta V_{\text {out }} \tag{3.110}
\end{equation*}
$$

[^9]Thus,

$$
\begin{equation*}
\Delta V_{\text {out }}=\frac{C_{1}}{C_{1}+C_{2}} \Delta V_{\text {in }} \tag{3.111}
\end{equation*}
$$

This result mirrors the voltage division formula for resistive dividers, except that $C_{1}$ (instead of $C_{2}$) appears in the numerator. Notably, the circuit in Fig. 3.54(a) is a specific instance of the capacitive divider with $C_{2}=0$ and, consequently, $\Delta V_{\text {out }}=\Delta V_{\text {in }}$.

In our initial steps towards constructing a voltage doubler, we should recall the outcome demonstrated in Fig. 3.31: the voltage across the diode in the peak detector exhibits an average value of $-V_{p}$ and, more significantly, a peak value of $-2 V_{p}$ (with respect to zero). For further examination, we rearrange the circuit as shown in Fig. 3.55, where the diode and capacitors are swapped, and the voltage across $D_{1}$ is denoted as $V_{\text {out }}$. Although $V_{\text {out }}$ in this configuration behaves identically to $V_{D 1}$ in Fig. 3.30(a), we analyze the output waveform from a different perspective to gain further insight.
